x4freetext: The data of the present work were corrected as
explained in REL-REF, where a more detailed
description on the corrections applied can be found.
Here only a short reminder is given.
The production rates are only partly corrected for
secondary reactions inside the production target. It is
assumed that secondary reactions, which are estimated
on the basis of the total reaction probability after
the first reaction, depopulate the nuclides in the
considered range, whereas the population due to
secondary reactions is assumed to appear in lighter
nuclei with Z<74 and could be neglected and is 5%.
The fluctuations within the isotopic distributions are
rather low. However, a few dips can be observed for
elements from thorium to astatine. Actually, the very
short time-of-flight of the ions, 150-ns eigen-time,
authorises the measurement of the production cross-
sections for most of the isotopes, namely when the
radioactive-decay period is much longer than the
time-of-flight of the ions. Only a few isotopes with
a number 128 neutrons decay by alpha emission towards
the 126-neutron shell and cause a dip in the apparent
cross sections. The decay period of those isotopes is
order of the TOF through the FRS . Therefore, part of
the production is lost before being analysed and
identified. Moreover, when the decay occurs at the very
beginning of theflight path, the ion is identified as
the daughter nucleus. This effect causes the slight
hump that can be observed for At-211 . It is not simple
to correct for this effect, since many of these nuclei
might be produced in isomeric states. Moreover, the
branching ratios and some of the associated decay
periods are not known. A couple of isotopes with a
number of 129 neutrons are also concerned. The very
fast decay of these nuclei, which prevents us from
giving true cross section in these few cases,
demonstrates the high quality of our data. This ensures
that the uncertainty is as low as claimed, since
effects of 10% to 20% can be observed. Moreover, we
guarante that the mass and charge identification is
correct.
.From the preprint
